         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">28/11/76 ¶  ¶ The Gramineae are gone since some time, dear Mr Bentham, by the "Shannon", and the Filices shall soon follow. By all means let General Munro have a full set or any duplicates of my Grami...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.11.28</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 189.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28/11/76</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The <name key="Gramineae">Gramineae</name> are gone since some time, dear Mr Bentham, by the "Shannon", and the <name key="Filices">Filices</name> shall soon follow. By all means let General Munro have a full set or any duplicates of my <name key="Gramineae">Gramineae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See G. Bentham to M, 20 September 1876.</p>
               </note> I grant this with all pleasure, not only because he is a careful worker, but because he does not take undue advantage of the work, merit and observations of others. What an advantage to every country of the globe it will be, when his universal treatment of the Grasses does appear.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Monro died in retirement at Taunton (Somerset) before the projected work could be completed; see <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' chronicle</seg>, n.s., vol. 13 (1880) p. 169.</p>
               </note> I think, that I mentioned before, that I changed my view on the sepaline nature of the bracteoles or ultimate bracts of gramineae since I worked on <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name>, and I have expressed myself to this effect at page 282 of vol VIII of the fragmenta already.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B74.13.01, under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Stipa aristiglumis.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>At last this month's mail brought me Drude's &amp; Wendlands dissertation on my Palms.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">H. Wendland &amp; Drude (1875).</p>
               </note> The limitation of the genera is too narrow, as you will likely observe by a mere walk through the Kew palm-house. What an unnecessary burden to the memory such superfluity of genera! How many intermediate species among <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">such</hi>
               </seg> genera may still be discovered. I do not know, at what date or even year this publication of W. &amp; D. appeared; but it must have been later than when I made my last remarks on Palms, wherein I brought myself <name key="Kentia%20Moorei">Kentia Moorei</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Kentia mooreana?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> to <name key="Clinostigma">Clinostigma</name>,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B74.09.02, p. 234-5.</p>
               </note> if that genus should be adopted. It seems strange, that these authors do not quote the note. As for <name key="Livistona%20Ramsayi">Livistona Ramsayi</name> it has no resemblance to L. inermis; the leaves indeed are like those of <name key="Licuala%20peltata">Licuala peltata</name> and Corypha [T]aliera; but with short indentations only, not cleft. Should not Licuala be reduced to Livistona? Can you kindly tell me, when Wendland's &amp; Drude's paper did appear?</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Zannichellia%20macrostemon">Zannichellia macrostemon</name> has a 4-celled anther. Hence <name key="Lepilaena">Lepilaena</name> may form a section only.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Assuredly palms have as little petals as <name key="Junceae">Junceae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will have observed that Scheffer has brought <name key="Laccospadix">Laccospadix</name> to <name key="Calyptrocalyx">Calyptrocalyx</name>.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Scheffer (1876).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
